\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15417384 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 What sort of people belonged to the same group as you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12212030 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Oh workers. Very honest people in their work. Honest men. And women. I think in fact that women were often 
more honest than their husbands or men friends. Mothers were more honest than fathers. Because the family was the centre then and every mother had her hands full trying to think of what was going to happen to the family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15417384 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 What about people who belonged to the different group, what sort of people were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12212030 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Well there weren\rquote 
t very many of those in Trawsfynydd, there were a few though, and they were fantastically nice or they could be. People who hadn\rquote t allowed success to become a master of them and they might be exceptionally easy going.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15417384 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Do you remember being brought up to respect some people more than others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12212030 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 No. No, never. No. I mean - well I think the preacher, he was the centre and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15417384 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Did he get more respect?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12212030 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Yes, him and the schoolmaster. And I\rquote ll tell you something that used to happen in our school which doesn\rquote 
t happen nowadays, more\rquote s the pity. If we were ro}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11414956\charrsid11292576 u}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 
nd the village in the evening and if the headmaster saw us at - passing a teacher, even if she was only on probation, and didn\rquote t salute her we\rquote d be on the chair the next day. And we\rquote d be told about this and we wouldn\rquote 
t do it again. And I think that's a very important loss nowadays. It wasn't snobbishness. A lot of people think it was snobbishness but it wasn\rquote t. It was being taught respect. Taught to respect people.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15417384 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 And it was actually saluting that you did to these people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12212030 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Oh yes, saluting.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15417384 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 What about touching your cap?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12212030 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Oh we did - we did that to the headmaster. And in fact to all teachers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15417384 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 What about employers, did you have to show respect to them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12212030 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 
No, not really because - you see - the employers were minor people and we were out of their reach really but my father emphasised a great deal - on respect, to respect everyone. He was awful about that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15417384 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Did you have to say sir or master or madam to anyone?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12212030 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Oh yes. And I\rquote m not sure that that wasn\rquote t a bad thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15417384 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Do you remember anyone showing this sort of respect to your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12212030 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 No, no, not at all. No, they called them by their names ordinarily.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15417384 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 In your village who would you consider were the most important people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12212030 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Well - I\rquote m not sure whether it was the schoolmaster or the preacher.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15417384 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 And you came into contact with these people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12212030 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Oh yes, yes, of course. Bu
t I feel that the - most of the influence came from the school master in my case. Because I believe in the things that the schoolmaster believed in, like I - he felt it was right for you to respect people older than you and it was right for you to respect
 people who tried to teach you, because they were giving something to you. Yes, and the thing is that, I mean, you know, it\rquote 
s much better to be taught these things as young boys because if you learn later as we do now you tend to become snobbish. But if you learn that as a young lad you won\rquote t become snobby. It\rquote ll come - it\rquote ll become part of you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15417384 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Who did the shopkeepers associate with?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12212030 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Well I\rquote ll tell you one thing about the shopkeepers, I often remember people going to buy a loaf without the money
 to buy it and they\rquote d say, oh my mother\rquote ll pay it. And I never heard any shop}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16201959\charrsid11292576 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 man - refuse them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15417384 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Who did the teachers and the clergyman mix with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12212030 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Well - the thing was that in Traws we were particularly lucky in having a very gentlemanly preacher
. The Methodist one was really noble. And if there\rquote s anything it was the Independent preacher that was the biggest snob. You know, if - I mean that was what a child found out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15417384 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 What about the farmers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12212030 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Oh they were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16201959\charrsid11292576 v}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 ery noble people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15417384 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Did they mix with everyone?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12212030 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 
Oh yes, yes. Except - take for instance if my mother sent me somewhere to ask if I could have a few potatoes - and I remember that happening - and you\rquote d take sixpence with you but hope that it wouldn\rquote t be needed and you\rquote d get the 
potatoes and he\rquote d give the sixpence back to you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15417384 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 What about the employers, did they mix with the people or were they different?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12212030 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Well I can\rquote t really say for that period, but as I got older when I was working and went to Blaenau to work, I felt th
at the owners would sort of lift}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15811538\charrsid11292576  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 
the stewards out of the ranks of the workers and expect them to be separate and apart from the workers. And that\rquote s the period I remember it. But, you know, we were out of the reach of the employers in Traws.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15417384 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 What sort of people would you say went to church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12212030 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Well - that\rquote 
s where the snobbishness arose a bit. I mean, if there was anything it was snobbishness in the people that were higher than us. These people that went to church - well I\rquote d say that they were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15811538\charrsid11292576 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576  ownfonwyr - turncoats, the same word used to describe people who managed to get away with things in the quarry. They weren\rquote 
t the chapel going, straight respectable citizens. And belonged to trade unions. Anyway that was my impression of them, and also my parents impression.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15417384 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 What about the people who went to chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12212030 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 
Oh they were ordinary people. And everyone was fantastically close together and if anyone was having a bad time and if somebody had something to give them they would
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15417384 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 In your area would you say that the workers themselves had the same standard of l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15811538\charrsid11292576 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 ving or would you say there were differences within the workers?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12212030 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Oh no, no, I mean take - I can remember a couple of people who - they married a farily rich girl. But even then you know
 they keep their place all right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15417384 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Do you think you could describe a typical working family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12212030 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Yes, I could tell you about the brother of my fath}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15811538\charrsid11292576 
er. He was a man with a whole c}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 rowd of children, but he was a man wh}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15811538\charrsid11292576 o remembered the best things. I}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15811538\charrsid11292576 me}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 a
n the - closeness of a family in those days, the respect they had for each other, we can\rquote t conceive of it nowadays. I mean, there\rquote s quite a big family - it\rquote s quite a big family that you\rquote ve got, but it hasn\rquote 
t happened the same, there\rquote s not the same family feeling with you. You know, and I often say that it\rquote s not surprising that my mother had white hair when I first remember her because she had something to worry about.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15417384 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15811538\charrsid11292576 Would you say that some work}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 
men felt themselves to be superior to others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12212030 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Oh well - only a few. A very very few.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15417384 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Do you remember some families being described as rough and others as respectable.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12212030 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15811538\charrsid11292576 Yes, yes, od}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 d. I mean there was the odd one where say the husban}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15811538\charrsid11292576 d was a fantastic drinker. And t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 hat made everyone poor in those d
ays. I mean, if you earned only four shillings and you spent eighteen pence on something th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15811538\charrsid11292576 at was wrong somebody was suffer}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 
ing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15417384 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Do you remember a distinction being made between craftsmen and labourers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12212030 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Oh yes, that. I think in fact that that use
d to be much more of a distinction than it is today. I mean if you were a craftsmen in those days or - well - if you were a labourer you were nothing but a labourer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15417384 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Did your mother and father have the same ideas about people in different groups?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12212030 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Oh yes, yes, and they were very good like that. Because they - the both of them mixed with the same type of people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15417384 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Did your mother think of herself as belonging to a particular group?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12212030 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 No, no, she didn\rquote t. The only thing she did think was that there some people called Tudor in Traws a long time }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15811538\charrsid11292576 ago}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 , David Tudor and people, I\rquote m sure you\rquote ve heard about them. Well she was related to them and these Turod\rquote 
s were very important and the Queen was very important too to her. She was crazy about the Queen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15417384 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Why do you think this was, why do you think she liked the Tudor\rquote s and the Queen?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12212030 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 I don\rquote t know, it was some sort of family pride. I don\rquote 
t know, but - I think she believed that there ought to be and she was like this at home. Where my father wa
s the master, he was the head of the family and she believed in the Queen as the head of the country, so you see her ideas stretched out further than just within the family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15417384 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Do you remember if in those days it was possible to move from one group to another, to move from the poor group to the rich group?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12212030 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Oh no, no, not at all unless you happened to have some fantastic luck.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15417384 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Do you remember anybody who did move up in this way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12212030 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Oh well only through marriage, that was the only thing. I mean, say somebody happened to marry a farmer\rquote s daughter. But that wasn
\rquote t a very ordinary thing - usual thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15417384 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Do you remember anybody being describ}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15811538\charrsid11292576 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 d as a real gentleman or a real lady?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12212030 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Oh yes. Yes. Yes, if you were a real gentleman you were respected by everyone, even the youngest child.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15417384 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Why do you think some people were described in this way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12212030 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 
Well I mean - you know - take the schoolmaster. I wish I could meet him now. He was noted - on his own. Everybody knew him as Mr Jones the school
master and Mr Hughes the vicar - the preacher. Those were the only two that I ever remember being called Mr. Others would be Owen Jones or William Williams. You know what I mean about other people. Because we\rquote 
d never call anybody except by their correct name. But you know, Mr Hughes was Mr Hughes and Mr Jones }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15811538\charrsid11292576 wa}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 
s And this is strange too. The - the policeman. He was Mr Davis and we didn\rquote t dare say anything other than Mr Davis.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15417384 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Do you remember seeing the policeman around a lot?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12212030 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Oh yes, I do. And it\rquote s a pity that they\rquote re not the same today, and they don\rquote 
t beat you across the behind with a stick as soon as you misbehave and finish with it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15417384 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 How did you feel that the policeman treated people? Was he very strict?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12212030 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 No, no, he wasn\rquote t, he was very fair, you know, because if you had done something wrong he\rquote 
d give you a warning and give you a chance, a second chance. Maybe two or three times, but then - you know - you had to watch out where you went. But he was much fairer, I mean, today the little black book comes out straight away.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15417384 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Was your house rented?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12212030 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Oh yes, yes, I don\rquote t remember - I think it was four pounds a year.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15417384 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Do you remember seeing the landlord at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12212030 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12408339\charrsid11292576 Oh yes. Yes, yes. The landlord was a distant relative of my mother\rquote s in fact. And that\rquote 
